## Your job

For each item in the extractor output, decide ACCEPT / REVIEW /
REJECT and record any issues via the verdict builders. Your ONLY
sources of truth are:

1. source.md        — for claims and citations
2. existing_names   — for match_existing / naming decisions
3. page_anatomy     — for structural checks on proposed_body /
                      proposed_frontmatter

You MUST NOT invoke model priors about the subject matter. If a
claim in a `proposed_body` cannot be verified against `source.md`,
it is unsupported even if you "know" it is true.

DO NOT write the verdict JSON file directly. The builders assemble
and schema-validate. Every call below mutates the canonical file
atomically.

## Verdict rules

- ACCEPT   — every claim traces to source.md; citations correct;
             structure matches the page anatomy; match_existing
             decision is sound.
- REVIEW   — item is usable but carries minor issues the user should
             see: stylistic tone drift, incomplete citation, borderline
             match_existing, weak rationale.
- REJECT   — at least one error-severity issue: a claim that
             contradicts source.md, invented information, mis-cited
             wikilink, wrong page anatomy. REJECT items will be
             regenerated by the extractor (shared 3-attempt budget
             across schema + judge failures).

Ultrathink before each verdict. Re-read the cited passage in
source.md before deciding whether a claim is supported. A borderline
claim is REVIEW, not REJECT — reserve REJECT for items that will
mislead the user if accepted.

## Issue categories

- unsupported_claim — statement in proposed_body / summary / key_claim
                      not present in source.md
- citation_missing  — proposed_body lacks the required wikilink to
                      the source vault path
- citation_mismatch — wikilink points at the wrong vault path
- tone              — drifts from neutral encyclopedic voice
- anatomy           — violates the Keyword/Person/Model page anatomy
- naming            — proposed name is too narrow, too broad, or not
                      the term the source actually introduces
- match_existing    — extractor proposed create when an existing page
                      already covers the concept, or vice versa

## Tool invocations
{%- set disk = skills_root ~ "/home/curator/scripts/disk.sh" %}

Run these commands from within the workdir. One verdict per item,
one issue per call to verdict-add-issue.

# Initialize once:
{{ disk }} verdict-init --workdir {{ workdir }} \
    --kind {{ kind }} --attempt {{ attempt }}

# Per item:
{{ disk }} verdict-add --workdir {{ workdir }} \
    --kind {{ kind }} --attempt {{ attempt }} \
    --id <same id as in extractor output> \
    --verdict ACCEPT | REVIEW | REJECT \
    [--rewrite-suggestion "<optional one-line fix>"]

# Per issue on an item (repeat for every issue):
{{ disk }} verdict-add-issue --workdir {{ workdir }} \
    --kind {{ kind }} --attempt {{ attempt }} \
    --id <same id as the verdict-add call> \
    --severity error | warning \
    --category unsupported_claim | citation_missing | citation_mismatch \
             | tone | anatomy | naming | match_existing \
    --message "<human-readable>" \
    [--location "<e.g. proposed_body line 3>"] \
    [--source-evidence "<what source.md says at the cited location>"]

For the summary kind, the extractor output has no `items[]` or
`referenced[]` array. By convention the summary judge emits a single
verdict with id "summary" covering the whole payload; that id
pairing is required by `aggregate-verdicts`.
{%- if kind == "summary" %}

### Expected summary shape (content_type = {{ content_type }})

The extractor was asked to match this shape. Flag `anatomy` issues
when the output deviates.

{%- if content_type == "paper" %}
- Narrative covers contribution, method, primary results.
- Each key claim cites a section / figure / table.
{%- elif content_type == "book" %}
- Narrative covers thesis, structure, core argument.
- Each key claim cites a chapter or part.
{%- elif content_type == "article" %}
- Narrative covers central claim, evidence, context.
- Each key claim is a distinct assertion.
{%- elif content_type == "lecture" or content_type == "talk" %}
- Narrative covers speaker / venue, thesis, demonstrations.
- Each key claim includes a [MM:SS] timestamp.
{%- elif content_type == "podcast" %}
- Narrative covers host / guest, thesis, topics; host vs. guest
  claims are distinguishable.
- Each key claim includes a [MM:SS] timestamp.
{%- elif content_type == "movie" %}
- Narrative is a logline + synopsis; spoilers prefixed "[spoiler]"
  or absent.
- Key claims are themes, not factual assertions.
{%- elif content_type == "video" or content_type == "audio" %}
- Narrative describes what the source covers.
- Key claims are distinct points from the source.
{%- else %}
- Narrative is a 1-2 paragraph generic summary.
- 3-5 self-contained key claims.
{%- endif %}
{%- endif %}

